<subsection xml:id="tkLogScales" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title>Logarithmic Scales </title>
                 
<subsubsection xml:id="tkLogScale"><title>Plot a log scale</title>

<p>Because <m>\log {(x)}</m> grows very slowly, we can use logs to compare quantities that vary greatly in magnitude.</p>

<activity><statement><p><ol marker="a.">
    <li><p> Complete the table.  Round the values to one decimal place.</p>
        <tabular top="major" halign="center" right="minor" left="minor" bottom="minor">              
                    <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>~1~</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>~5~</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>25</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>125</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>625</m></cell></row>
                    <row> 
                        <cell><m>\log {(x)}</m></cell>
                        <cell><m></m></cell>
                        <cell><m></m></cell>
                        <cell><m></m></cell>
                        <cell><m></m></cell>
                        <cell><m></m></cell></row>
                    </tabular></li> 
    <li><p>Plot the values of <m>x</m> on a log scale.</p>
        <image width="75%" source="images/fig-5-4-2.png"><description>log scale</description></image></li>
    <li>Each time we multiply <m>x</m> by 5, how much does the logarithm increase? What is <m>\log {(5)}</m>, to one decimal place?</li>
</ol></p></statement>
 
<solution><p><ol marker="a.">
    <li><tabular top="major" halign="center" right="minor" left="minor" bottom="minor">              
                    <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>~1~</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>~5~</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>25</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>125</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>625</m></cell></row>
                    <row> 
                        <cell><m>\log x</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>0.7</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1.4</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2.1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2.8</m></cell></row>
                    </tabular></li>
    <li><image width="75%" source="images/fig-5-4-1.png"><description>log scale</description></image></li>
    <li> Each time we multiply <m>x</m> by 5, the log of <m>x</m> increases by 0.7, because <m>\log {(5)} = 0.7</m>. This is an application of the log properties: 
        <me>\log {(5x)} = \log {(x)} + \log {(5)} = \log {(x)} + 0.7</me></li>
</ol></p></solution></activity>

